  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equations.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\Pi_{JJ}(\\omega)\n=\n\\int\ndt\\,\ne^{i\\omega t}\n\\langle J(t)J(0)\\rangle .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\sigma(\\omega)\n=\n\\frac{1}{\\omega}\n\\operatorname{Im}\\Pi_{JJ}(\\omega).\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $J(t)$ be a current operator.  \nThe current--current response function is obtained by Fourier transforming the correlation:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\Pi_{JJ}(\\omega)\n=\n\\int\ndt\\,\ne^{i\\omega t}\n\\langle J(t)J(0)\\rangle .\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe transport coefficient is then extracted from the dissipative part of that correlator:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\n\\sigma(\\omega)\n=\n\\frac{1}{\\omega}\n\\operatorname{Im}\\Pi_{JJ}(\\omega).\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nTransport coefficients arise from quantum current correlations rather than from purely classical response laws.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
